Note:
============================================================================
DISPATCHER-CONTRACT ALIASES (P2-B Wave 1 backfill)
============================================================================

The 66-proc bare-name dispatcher in compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/
syscall.runa requires every platform export the same surface (SYS_BRK,
SYS_EXIT_GROUP, SYS_GETPID, SYS_GETUID, SYS_GETGID, ...). NetBSD's
syscalls.master uses different historical names for these (obreak,
getpid_with_ppid, getuid_with_euid, etc.). The procs below expose the
dispatcher-contract names while returning the NetBSD-native syscall
numbers (or sentinels where NetBSD has no native equivalent).

Source: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h (NetBSD-10 src tree).
NetBSD shares the same syscall table across architectures (aarch64 and
amd64 dispatch the same numeric entries via per-arch trap glue), so the
numeric values are identical to netbsd_x64/syscall.runa.
:End Note

@Reasoning
NetBSD does not export a bare `brk(2)` syscall under that name; the historical
heap-pointer expansion entry is `obreak` at number 17 (visible in
sys/sys/syscall.h as `SYS_obreak`). The dispatcher's bare-name contract uses
`SYS_BRK` (Linux-style), so this proc forwards to NetBSD's `obreak` number.
The semantics match: `obreak(addr)` sets the process data segment break to
`addr` and returns 0 on success, -1 on failure (with errno via the libc
shim). Callers that need POSIX-modern heap growth on NetBSD should prefer
`syscall_mmap` with MAP_ANON|MAP_PRIVATE, but the bare-name dispatcher must
resolve to a real syscall so cross-target compilation does not break.
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h entry `SYS_obreak = 17`; NetBSD `obreak(2)`
historical man page (now retired in libc but still present in the kernel).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns the constant 17 directly. The actual brk(2) ABI on aarch64 NetBSD is
issued by `syscall_brk` below: load 17 into X8, the new break address into X0,
issue `svc #0`, examine X0 for negative-on-error. This proc is a pure number
provider with no side effects; the syscall_N helpers do the assembly.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
This proc is invoked once per `syscall_brk` call to retrieve the syscall
number. It is a leaf returning a literal; the codegen should inline it at the
call site after monomorphization. No allocation, no I/O, no branch — the cost
floor is a single `mov` + `ret` (or a constant fold into the X8 register
setup, eliminating the call entirely).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
`obreak(2)` adjusts the process address space. Misuse can grow the heap into
the stack guard region or shrink it across in-use allocations, leading to
corruption. The kernel enforces rlimit RLIMIT_DATA on growth; userland must
not pass an addr below the current break boundary unless freeing intentional
heap. This proc does not validate the addr passed to `syscall_brk` — that
responsibility lives in the caller (runtime/core/memory.runa on NetBSD).
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_SYS_BRK" returns Integer:
    Return 17
End Process

@Reasoning
NetBSD has no `exit_group(2)` syscall. Linux introduced `exit_group` to
terminate every thread in a thread-group atomically; NetBSD achieves the same
effect by having `exit(2)` itself terminate the whole process (since NetBSD
threads are kernel-LWPs that share the proc structure, and proc-level `exit`
cascades through `lwp_exit_switchaway` to every LWP). The dispatcher contract
requires `SYS_EXIT_GROUP` to exist; on NetBSD it resolves to the same number
as `SYS_EXIT` (1), preserving the "terminate the whole process" semantic
without requiring a separate kernel entry point.
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h entry `SYS_exit = 1`; NetBSD kern/kern_exit.c
`sys_exit()` implementation (terminates all LWPs in the proc).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 (NetBSD `SYS_exit`). When invoked via the bare-name dispatcher, the
caller's `syscall_1(SYS_EXIT_GROUP, status)` issues `svc #0` with X8=1 and
X0=status, which the NetBSD kernel routes to `sys_exit`, terminating every
LWP in the process group.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Leaf returning a literal; inlined post-monomorphization. The actual syscall
is one-way (no return) — the kernel never resumes the caller — so the cost
metric is "trap latency to process teardown," dominated by LWP-teardown
walk, not by this number-fetch.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
exit(2) terminates the calling process. No additional privilege boundary
crossed by this number-fetch. The kernel handles cleanup of file descriptors,
shared memory mappings, and child-process reaping. No userland resource leak
is possible from a successful exit.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_SYS_EXIT_GROUP" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
The dispatcher contract uses the bare name `SYS_GETPID` (Linux-style).
NetBSD's syscalls.master exports `SYS_getpid_with_ppid = 20` (the
NetBSD-extended form returning both pid and ppid via X0 and X1 on aarch64);
the historical `SYS_getpid = 20` is the same numeric entry — invoking it
yields the pid in X0 regardless of whether the caller consumes the X1 ppid.
Number 20 is therefore the correct dispatcher-contract value.
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h entry `SYS_getpid_with_ppid = 20`; NetBSD
kern/sys_descrip.c `sys_getpid_with_ppid()` (sets retval[0]=pid,
retval[1]=ppid; aarch64 ABI delivers these in X0 and X1 respectively).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 20 directly. `syscall_0(SYS_GETPID)` loads 20 into X8, issues
`svc #0`, and reads pid from X0 on return.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Leaf, inlined. The kernel `sys_getpid_with_ppid` is a fast-path read of
`p->p_pid` (and `p->p_pptr->p_pid` for ppid); aarch64 trap-and-return is the
dominant cost. NetBSD does not cache pid in a vDSO-style page (as Linux does
on some architectures), so each call traps.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
getpid(2) discloses the process id, a value already visible in /proc, ps
output, and audit logs; no privilege boundary is crossed. The syscall always
succeeds and has no side effects on process state.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_SYS_GETPID" returns Integer:
    Return 20
End Process

@Reasoning
Dispatcher contract bare-name `SYS_GETUID`. NetBSD exports
`SYS_getuid_with_euid = 24` (the NetBSD form returning both uid and euid via
X0 and X1); the historical `SYS_getuid = 24` is the same kernel entry.
Number 24 is the correct dispatcher value.
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h entry `SYS_getuid_with_euid = 24`; NetBSD
kern/kern_prot.c `sys_getuid_with_euid()` (sets retval[0]=ruid,
retval[1]=euid).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 24. Caller's `syscall_0(SYS_GETUID)` issues svc #0 with X8=24; X0
holds the real uid on return.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Leaf, inlined. kernel side is a credential-struct field read (no locking
because the cred is COW per-proc on NetBSD); trap latency dominates.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
getuid(2) discloses the calling user's real uid, already visible to the user.
No privilege check needed. The syscall cannot fail.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_SYS_GETUID" returns Integer:
    Return 24
End Process

@Reasoning
Dispatcher contract bare-name `SYS_GETGID`. NetBSD exports
`SYS_getgid_with_egid = 47` (returning both gid and egid in X0 and X1);
historical `SYS_getgid = 47` is the same kernel entry. Number 47 is correct.
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h entry `SYS_getgid_with_egid = 47`; NetBSD
kern/kern_prot.c `sys_getgid_with_egid()`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 47. Caller's `syscall_0(SYS_GETGID)` issues svc #0 with X8=47; X0
holds the real gid on return.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Leaf, inlined. Same fast-path semantics as SYS_GETUID — kernel reads cred
struct field, trap latency dominates.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
getgid(2) discloses the calling process's real group id. No privilege
boundary; the syscall cannot fail.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_SYS_GETGID" returns Integer:
    Return 47
End Process

