Note:
============================================================================
MEMORY MAPPING FLAGS
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "netbsd_arm64_MAP_SHARED" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Share changes
End Process

Process called "netbsd_arm64_MAP_PRIVATE" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: Changes are private
End Process

Process called "netbsd_arm64_MAP_FIXED" returns Integer:
    Return 16  Note: Interpret addr exactly
End Process

Process called "netbsd_arm64_MAP_ANON" returns Integer:
    Return 4096  Note: Anonymous memory (not file-backed)
End Process

Process called "netbsd_arm64_MAP_STACK" returns Integer:
    Return 8192  Note: Region grows down (stack)
End Process

Process called "netbsd_arm64_MAP_FILE" returns Integer:
    Return 0  Note: File mapping (default)
End Process

@Reasoning
Dispatcher-contract alias for NetBSD's MAP_ANON. Linux exports both
MAP_ANONYMOUS and MAP_ANON as a single flag (0x20); BSDs historically use
only MAP_ANON. The 66-proc dispatcher requires MAP_ANONYMOUS to exist as a
bare name on every platform. On NetBSD aarch64 (and amd64), MAP_ANON is
0x1000 = 4096 per sys/sys/mman.h, distinct from Linux's 0x20. This proc
returns the NetBSD value so that callers passing
`MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS` to syscall_mmap get the correct kernel-recognized
flag combination.
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/mman.h `#define MAP_ANON 0x1000`. Confirmed
identical on aarch64 (NetBSD shares mman.h across architectures).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 4096 directly (0x1000). Bitwise-OR into the `flags` argument of
syscall_mmap: e.g. `syscall_mmap(0, len, prot, MAP_PRIVATE()|MAP_ANONYMOUS(),
-1, 0)` produces flags = 2 | 4096 = 4098, the canonical anonymous private
mapping on NetBSD aarch64.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Leaf returning literal. Inlined post-monomorphization; the OR operation in
the caller becomes a single immediate-or on the flags register.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
MAP_ANONYMOUS requests memory not backed by any file. The kernel zeros the
returned pages before mapping (POSIX guarantee, enforced by NetBSD
`uvm_pagealloc_strat` ZERO path). No information leak from prior owners.
The flag itself does not grant privilege; the surrounding `syscall_mmap`
call's prot bitmap determines read/write/exec.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_MAP_ANONYMOUS" returns Integer:
    Return 4096
End Process

@Reasoning
POSIX file mode 0644 octal = rw-r--r-- (owner rw, group r, other r). Decimal
value 420. NetBSD encodes file mode bits identically to every POSIX system
(the bottom 9 bits of the mode_t encode rwxrwxrwx in standard order). This
constant is invoked by callers of `syscall_open` with the O_CREAT flag, who
need a numeric mode argument; exposing it as a proc avoids hardcoding magic
numbers at every call site.
Source: POSIX.1-2017 sys_stat_h S_IRUSR/S_IWUSR/S_IRGRP/S_IROTH; NetBSD
sys/sys/stat.h identical encoding.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 420 = 0o644 = (0o400|0o200|0o040|0o004) = (S_IRUSR|S_IWUSR|S_IRGRP|
S_IROTH). Caller passes this as the third arg to `syscall_open` when
O_CREAT is in the flags bitmap.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Leaf, inlined. The mode argument is consumed only when the kernel creates a
new vnode (O_CREAT path); for existing files it is ignored.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
0644 is the standard "world-readable, owner-writable" mode for regular
files. Callers that create files containing sensitive data must use 0600
(S_IRUSR|S_IWUSR only) instead. This proc itself does not perform any
privileged operation.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_MODE_0644" returns Integer:
    Return 420
End Process

@Reasoning
POSIX file mode 0755 octal = rwxr-xr-x (owner rwx, group rx, other rx).
Decimal 493. Used by `syscall_mkdir` and `syscall_open` (with O_CREAT for
executable scripts). NetBSD encodes identically to POSIX.
Source: POSIX.1-2017 sys_stat_h; NetBSD sys/sys/stat.h.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 493 = 0o755 = (0o400|0o200|0o100|0o040|0o010|0o004|0o001).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Leaf, inlined.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
0755 grants execute permission to all users and write only to the owner.
Standard mode for directories and executables. Callers creating
security-sensitive directories (e.g. private state) must use 0700 instead.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_MODE_0755" returns Integer:
    Return 493
End Process

@Reasoning
lseek(2) whence value 0: "the offset is set to offset bytes from the
beginning of the file." POSIX-standard; NetBSD uses the identical numeric
constant in sys/sys/unistd.h `SEEK_SET = 0`. The dispatcher-contract proc
exposes this value uniformly across platforms.
Source: POSIX.1-2017 unistd.h SEEK_SET; NetBSD sys/sys/unistd.h.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 0 literal.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Leaf, inlined.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
SEEK_SET with offset 0 is the canonical "rewind to start." No privilege
boundary. Callers must validate offset is non-negative before passing to
syscall_lseek to avoid EINVAL.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_SEEK_SET" returns Integer:
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
lseek(2) whence value 1: "the offset is set to its current location plus
offset bytes." POSIX-standard. NetBSD sys/sys/unistd.h `SEEK_CUR = 1`.
Source: POSIX.1-2017 unistd.h SEEK_CUR; NetBSD sys/sys/unistd.h.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 literal.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Leaf, inlined.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
SEEK_CUR allows relative repositioning. No privilege check; the kernel
clamps the resulting offset to a non-negative value or returns EINVAL.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_SEEK_CUR" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
lseek(2) whence value 2: "the offset is set to the size of the file plus
offset bytes." POSIX-standard. NetBSD sys/sys/unistd.h `SEEK_END = 2`.
Used by callers needing "append-at-end" or end-of-file size queries
(`lseek(fd, 0, SEEK_END)` returns file size).
Source: POSIX.1-2017 unistd.h SEEK_END; NetBSD sys/sys/unistd.h.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 2 literal.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Leaf, inlined.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
SEEK_END with positive offset creates a sparse "hole" between EOF and the
new position; subsequent reads of the hole return zeros. No privilege
escalation; standard POSIX behavior.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_SEEK_END" returns Integer:
    Return 2
End Process

