Note:
============================================================================
DISPATCHER-CONTRACT SYSCALL_X WRAPPERS (P2-B Wave 1 backfill)
============================================================================

These wrappers expose the canonical `syscall_<name>` entry points the
66-proc dispatcher requires every platform to provide. They forward to
the existing aarch64 syscall_N helpers above with the NetBSD-native
syscall number. They differ from the higher-level wrappers (`read`,
`write`, etc.) only in name — the dispatcher routes by `syscall_<name>`
bare name.
:End Note

@Reasoning
Wraps the NetBSD `read(2)` syscall (number 3) for the dispatcher's
`syscall_read` contract. Loads SYS_READ into X8, fd into X0, buffer into X1,
count into X2, issues svc #0, returns X0. On success X0 holds the byte count
read (possibly 0 for EOF); on error X0 is negative -errno (typically -EBADF,
-EINTR, -EIO, etc.). Caller responsibility: check is_error(result) before
treating the value as a count.
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h `SYS_read = 3`; NetBSD sys/kern/sys_generic.c
sys_read() implementation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegates to syscall_3 helper with SYS_READ() as the first argument. The
helper performs the X8 load, X0-X2 argument marshalling, svc #0 trap, and
result extraction in inline assembly. No buffer validation occurs here; the
kernel's copyout path validates the user-space pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One indirect call (the SYS_READ() proc, which constant-folds to 3) and one
direct call to syscall_3. The latter is the only un-elidable cost: it issues
the SVC trap, which switches mode, executes the kernel side, and returns.
Trap latency on a modern aarch64 CPU is roughly 300-800 cycles plus kernel
work. For small reads the bottleneck is the trap, not the copy.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Reads bytes from a kernel-managed file descriptor into a user buffer. The
kernel validates fd ownership, buffer writability, and descriptor mode.
Userland must ensure the buffer points to a region at least count bytes
wide and writable, or the kernel returns EFAULT.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_syscall_read" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Return netbsd_arm64_syscall_3(netbsd_arm64_SYS_READ(), fd, buffer, count)
End Process

@Reasoning
Wraps NetBSD `write(2)` (syscall 4) for the dispatcher's `syscall_write`
contract. X8=4, X0=fd, X1=buffer, X2=count, svc #0, return X0 (bytes
written, or -errno negative).
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h `SYS_write = 4`; sys/kern/sys_generic.c
sys_write().
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegates to syscall_3 with SYS_WRITE() as the number argument.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Same as syscall_read: trap latency dominates for small writes. For large
writes the kernel's copyin loop dominates.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Writes from a user buffer to a kernel-managed fd. Kernel validates fd
ownership, buffer readability (EFAULT on bad pointer), and fd write mode.
Caller must ensure the buffer remains valid for count bytes through the
trap.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_syscall_write" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Return netbsd_arm64_syscall_3(netbsd_arm64_SYS_WRITE(), fd, buffer, count)
End Process

@Reasoning
Wraps NetBSD `open(2)` (syscall 5). NetBSD aarch64 retains the
three-argument open(path, flags, mode) form (unlike Linux arm64, which
only exposes openat). X8=5, X0=path pointer, X1=flags, X2=mode, svc #0,
return X0 (fd >= 0 on success, -errno on error).
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h `SYS_open = 5`; sys/kern/vfs_syscalls.c
sys_open().
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegates to syscall_3 with SYS_OPEN().
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Path lookup is the dominant cost: namei walks the file system from the
root or process cwd, traversing one vnode lookup per path component.
Cached lookups are fast; uncached lookups incur disk reads.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
File open enforces per-file mode/ACL via the VFS layer. Callers passing
O_CREAT must also pass a sane mode. Symbolic links along the path are
followed unless O_NOFOLLOW is in flags; opening untrusted paths must use
O_NOFOLLOW plus stat-then-open to avoid symlink TOCTOU.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_syscall_open" takes filename as Integer, flags as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    Return netbsd_arm64_syscall_3(netbsd_arm64_SYS_OPEN(), filename, flags, mode)
End Process

@Reasoning
Wraps NetBSD `close(2)` (syscall 6). X8=6, X0=fd, svc #0, return X0 (0 on
success, -errno on error).
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h `SYS_close = 6`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegates to syscall_1 with SYS_CLOSE().
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Cheap: fd-table slot reclaim plus vnode reference drop. Drop may trigger
dirty-buffer flush if the fd was the last reference; usually deferred to
buffer-cache flushing path, not synchronous.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
close(2) on an fd not owned by the proc returns EBADF without side
effects. Callers must not retain stale fd values past their close to
avoid double-close hazards if the fd is reused.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_syscall_close" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Return netbsd_arm64_syscall_1(netbsd_arm64_SYS_CLOSE(), fd)
End Process

@Reasoning
Wraps NetBSD `exit(2)` (syscall 1). One-way trap: the kernel never returns
to the caller; the LWP teardown path tears down every LWP in the proc and
delivers SIGCHLD to the parent. X8=1, X0=status, svc #0.
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h `SYS_exit = 1`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegates to syscall_1 with SYS_EXIT(). The return is unreachable in
practice (kernel never returns); the Runa type system requires a return
value, so the assembly path stores whatever X0 contains post-trap.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Performance is irrelevant — the trap terminates the calling thread.
Kernel teardown cost is invisible to the now-dead caller.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
exit(2) is unconditionally permitted to the calling process. No
privilege boundary. The kernel reaps all process resources; no userland
resource leak is possible from a successful exit.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_arm64_syscall_exit" takes status as Integer returns Integer:
    Return netbsd_arm64_syscall_1(netbsd_arm64_SYS_EXIT(), status)
End Process

@Reasoning
Wraps NetBSD `obreak(2)` via SYS_BRK = 17. Adjusts the process data
segment break to addr. X8=17, X0=addr, svc #0, return X0 (0 on success or
new break addr, -errno on failure). Modern NetBSD userland uses
mmap-based heap allocation; this is provided for ABI completeness.
